          Martha and Sally each have the same amount of money.

          If Martha spends £10\pounds 10£10 and sally spends £20\pounds 20£20, then Martha has three times as much as Sally.

          If Martha spends £15\pounds 15£15 and Sally spends £20\pounds 20£20, then Martha has twice as much as Sally.

          how much money do they have altogether?

          Let money Martha has be m and Sally has be s,

          m−10=3×(s−20)m−10=3s−603s−m=50m=3s−50\begin{aligned} m - 10 = 3 \times (s - 20) \\\\ m - 10 = 3s - 60 \\\\ 3s - m = 50 \\\\ m = 3s -50 \end{aligned}m−10=3×(s−20)m−10=3s−603s−m=50m=3s−50​

          m−15=2×(s−20)m−15=2s−402s−m=25\begin{aligned} m - 15 = 2 \times (s - 20) \\\\ m - 15 = 2s - 40 \\\\ 2s - m = 25 \end{aligned}m−15=2×(s−20)m−15=2s−402s−m=25​

          Replacing m in second question

          2s−3s+50=25s=25\begin{aligned} 2s - 3s + 50 = 25 \\\\ s = 25 \end{aligned}2s−3s+50=25s=25​

          Value of m will be, m=3s−50m=75−50m=25\begin{aligned} m = 3s - 50 \\\\ m = 75 - 50 \\\\ m = 25 \end{aligned}m=3s−50m=75−50m=25​

          Total money both has, =25+25=£50\begin{aligned} &= 25 + 25 \\\\ &= \pounds 50 \end{aligned}​=25+25=£50​
